        "text": "Marc Maufort\n\nAlthough Eugene O'Neill owes his fame to plays of novelistic proportions such as The Iceman Cometh and Long Day's Journey into Night, his importance as a master of the one-acter genre should not be underestimated. Critics, with the notable exceptions of Travis Bogard and Paul Voelker C), have often failed to recognize the pivotal role of these miniature plays in the development of O'Neill's dramaturgy. For the most part, these one-acters can be regarded as embryonic expressions of themes which the writer formulates through more intricate designs in his full-fledged dramas. A case in point is offered by two short works belonging to different periods of the artist's career, Bound East for Cardiff (1916) and Hughie (1941), the latter being aptly subtitled \"By Way of Obit\". O'Neill once confessed to Richard Dana Skinner that Bound East for Cardiff was \"very important from my point of view. In it can be seen, or felt, the germ of the spirit, life attitude, etc., of all my more important future work\" (2). And indeed, Bound East for Cardiff, and Hughie constitute mature and concentrated recapitulations of the dramatist's life-long obsession with mortality, a motif recurring in practically all his longer works. In Bound East for Cardiff, an episode of the \"S. S. Glencairn\" cycle, a poor sailor named Yank meets with death in the comforting presence of his old friend Driscoll. An almost identical pattern reemerges in Hughie as Erie, a teller of tales, bemoans"
